<DocsLayout title="How the compiler works" description="How canonical React Kumo observations become native framework packages with packed SSR, hydration, and browser receipts.">
<p class="eyebrow">Explanation</p>
<h1>How the compiler works</h1>
<p class="lede">The compiler ports recorded Kumo behavior. It does not translate arbitrary React source.</p>

<h2>What it does</h2>
<ol>
<li>Observe the pinned canonical React package and record executable <code>kumo.observable/v1</code> contracts.</li>
<li>Derive framework-neutral component models and behavior capabilities.</li>
<li>Emit native Vue, Svelte, and Solid source under fixed downstream package identities.</li>
<li>Install each packed tarball and run SSR, hydration, trusted browser interaction, node-identity, and diagnostic checks.</li>
<li>Record every component-by-target result as <code>passed</code>, <code>failed</code>, <code>blocked</code>, or <code>not-run</code>.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>A generated file or successful build is not parity.</strong> Only a <code>passed</code> packed-package receipt supports a parity claim.</p>

<h2>How it is built</h2>
<div class="source-grid">
<a href={`${source}/contracts/kumo.observable/v1/`}><strong>Observable contracts</strong><span>Executable behavior and provenance.</span></a>
<a href={`${source}/src/kumo/library/`}><strong>Library algebra</strong><span>Framework-neutral state and behavior capabilities.</span></a>
<a href={`${source}/src/kumo/emitters/`}><strong>Native emitters</strong><span>Vue, Svelte, and Solid source generation.</span></a>
<a href={`${source}/scripts/observable-browser-runner.mjs`}><strong>Browser runner</strong><span>Trusted CDP input, hydration, diagnostics, and receipts.</span></a>
<a href={`${source}/proof/dx/conformance/`}><strong>Conformance fixtures</strong><span>Neutral vectors and target receipts.</span></a>
</div>
<p>Generated files are disposable. Fixes belong in a contract, shared capability, emitter, fixture, or runner, then flow through regeneration and packed proof.</p>

<h2>Where it is useful</h2>
<ul>
<li>Preserving one pinned behavioral authority while native targets evolve independently.</li>
<li>Separating shared behavior from framework syntax.</li>
<li>Locating failures at the contract, emitter, package, hydration, or browser boundary.</li>
<li>Adding a target without weakening the component-by-target evidence matrix.</li>
</ul>
<p>Components outside the recorded contracts are outside the compiler's claim.</p>

<h2>Adding a target</h2>
<ol>
<li>Define an adapter and native emitter against the existing contracts and algebra.</li>
<li>Add target comparison pages.</li>
<li>Earn the complete executable component-by-target matrix with the same packed SSR, hydration, and browser receipts.</li>
</ol>
<p>An adapter, emitted tree, build, or comparison page alone does not establish support.</p>
</DocsLayout>
